olved, “normative” Judaism is now understood to be the result of one approach having achieved prominence over many others, competing for acceptance in the wake of the destruction of the Jerusalem Temple in the year 70 CE. This new understanding has implications for how we think about Judaism today, as the collapse of rabbinic authority is leading to the return of the kind of diversity that prevailed during late antiquity. This volume puts familiar aspects of Judaism in a new light, exposing readers to the most current understanding of the origins of normative Judaism. This book is a must for anyone interested in the study of Judaism and its formation. It is the most current review of the scholarship surrounding this rich history and what is next for the field at large.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aJudaismxHistoryyPost-exilic period, 586 B.C.-210 A.D. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh1 aFine, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldenberg, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenspahn, Frederick E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenspahn, Frederick E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGruen, Erich S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayes, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHimmelfarb, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanger, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReinhartz, Adele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwartz, Seth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShanks Alexander, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca